<TITLE> UK-based lawyers seek free judiciary on schedule </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 London, Oct23 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladeshi barristers and solicitors working in the UK Monday asked Bangladesh government to go ahead with the planned separation of the judiciary from the executive. The demand came from a meeting held at Woodeham Community Hall at East London). It was chaired by solicitor and former advocate of High Court Sohul Ahmed. Barrister Ataur Rahman, solicitor and High Court advocate M Abul Kalam, barrister Nazir Ahmed, solicitor Taz Shah, former senior assistant judge barrister Enamul Haq and barrister Kalam Chowdhury, among others, spoke at the meeting. The meeting condemned the move by some administrative magistrates to halt the process of separation scheduled for Nov 1. It urged the government to take drastic action against those who acted against the direction of the landmark Supreme Court directive. The speakers also stressed the need to carve out a free judiciary to ensure everyone's access to fair and transparent justice. b
